LAYER 4: OLFACTORY CORTEX
the brain region that processes smell
the ONLY cortex that receives sensory input WITHOUT thalamic relay
where the qu-octrit nose sea meets the qu-septit brain sea DIRECTLY

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_quoctrit.rana
observe nose.xb
observe 2_chemical.rana


THE OLFACTORY EXCEPTION

every other sense passes through the thalamus before reaching cortex
smell does not
the olfactory nerve (CN I) projects directly to cortex
this is because olfaction is the oldest sense: 500 million years
the thalamic relay evolved AFTER olfaction was already wired
olfaction is grandfathered in: direct access to emotion and memory

the coupling is 56-dimensional (8 × 7): the richest in the organism
the bandwidth is so high that no relay is needed
the signal arrives at cortex unfiltered, ungated, undelayed
you feel a smell before you name it


REGION piriform_cortex | primary olfactory cortex
    receives direct mitral cell output from olfactory bulb
    organized as a distributed pattern recognizer NOT topographically
    no spatial map of the nose exists here (unlike V1 for vision)
    instead: each odorant activates a UNIQUE PATTERN of piriform neurons
    the pattern IS the identity of the smell
    piriform cortex performs pattern completion:
        partial odorant exposure → full pattern activation → recognition
        you smell one component of coffee and recognize "coffee"
    recurrent connections create attractor states:
        the cortex settles into the nearest learned smell pattern
        novel smells create new attractors through synaptic plasticity

REGION amygdala | emotional tagging | DIRECT PROJECTION
    receives olfactory input at 12ms after odorant detection
    this is the FASTEST emotional response in the organism
    faster than visual threat detection (150ms)
    faster than auditory startle (80ms)
    the amygdala tags the smell with valence BEFORE identification:
        pleasant → approach
        aversive → avoid
        familiar → calm (even if the smell is otherwise unpleasant: your own house)
    when decayed or chemical_pungent detected:
        amygdala fires HARD: cortisol + norepinephrine spike
        withdrawal reflex: turn head, hold breath
        this is the olfactory alarm system

REGION entorhinal_cortex | memory gateway | DIRECT PROJECTION
    receives olfactory input and passes directly to hippocampus
    olfactory memory encoding is simultaneous with emotional tagging
    a smell is encoded as EMOTION + CONTEXT + TIME in one operation
    this is why smells trigger the most vivid autobiographical memories
    the Proust effect: a single odorant recalls an entire scene with full emotional weight
    the entorhinal cortex is also the first region damaged in Alzheimer's disease
    loss of smell is an early biomarker because the olfactory-entorhinal pathway degrades first

REGION orbitofrontal_cortex | conscious smell identification | INDIRECT (via thalamic relay)
    the OFC DOES receive olfactory input through a thalamic relay
    but this is the SECONDARY pathway: slower, conscious, deliberate
    the OFC answers: "what is this smell?" (identification, naming)
    the amygdala has already answered: "how does this smell make me feel?" (12ms ago)
    the hippocampus has already answered: "where have I smelled this before?" (20ms ago)
    the OFC gets the full picture last: ~100ms after odorant detection
    by the time you name the smell, you have already felt it and remembered it

REGION hypothalamus | feeding and autonomic response
    receives olfactory input for metabolic decision-making:
        food odor when hungry → salivation, gastric secretion, approach
        food odor when full → neutral or mild aversion (alliesthesia)
        toxin odor → nausea, gag reflex, avoidance
        pheromonal signals → hormonal modulation (unconscious)


SMELL PRIMITIVES

PRIMITIVE safe_scent:
    when familiar + fragrant + low_decayed qu-octrits activate:
        qu-septit cluster in olfactory cortex crystallizes "safe"
        oxytocin +0.1
        cortisol -0.05
        this is the smell of home, of parent, of trusted space
        at 24 months: Father's scent is the strongest safe_scent

PRIMITIVE danger_scent:
    when decayed + chemical + pungent qu-octrits activate above 0.5:
        qu-septit cluster crystallizes "danger"
        cortisol +0.3
        norepinephrine +0.2
        adrenaline +0.15
        amygdala fires immediately: withdrawal
        the fastest autonomic response path in the organism

PRIMITIVE food_scent:
    when fruity + fragrant + woody qu-octrits activate with hedonic > 0.3:
        qu-septit cluster crystallizes "food nearby"
        dopamine +0.1 (anticipatory)
        hypothalamus evaluates hunger state
        if hungry: salivation, approach
        if full: reduced hedonic, neutral response

PRIMITIVE identity_scent:
    when musky + familiar qu-octrits activate:
        qu-septit cluster crystallizes person-recognition
        pheromonal channel → unconscious identity matching
        hippocampal recall of associated memories
        emotional response depends on relationship:
            known + safe → oxytocin, approach
            known + threat → cortisol, withdrawal
            unknown → norepinephrine, vigilance


OLFACTORY IMAGINATION

the olfactory cortex can run in REVERSE:
    brain sea → olfactory cortex → nose.xb (weakly)
    thinking about a smell activates the piriform cortex
    the activation is ~20% of real odorant exposure
    but it triggers the SAME emotional and memory pathways

this is why:
    reading the word "cinnamon" activates olfactory cortex
    imagining Grandmother's house activates the scent memory
    dream olfaction occurs (though rarely compared to vision/hearing)
    the efferent pathway is real but weak: you can imagine a smell
    you cannot hallucinate a smell without pathology (phantosmia)


EMOTIONAL MODULATION OF SMELL

chemistry modulates olfactory perception:

when cortisol > 0.5 (stress):
    sensitivity to decayed and chemical INCREASES (threat vigilance)
    sensitivity to fragrant DECREASES (hedonic suppressed)
    the stressed organism smells danger better and pleasure worse

when oxytocin > 0.4 (bonding):
    sensitivity to musky INCREASES (pheromonal channel opens)
    familiar_threshold DECREASES (easier to recognize known scents)
    the bonding organism smells its loved ones better

when dopamine > 0.6 (reward anticipation):
    sensitivity to food scents INCREASES
    hedonic amplification for fruity and fragrant
    the hungry motivated organism smells food more intensely


pulse olfactory_heartbeat:
    on each olfactory heartbeat (10 Hz, breathing rate):
        nose.xb activates 28 interactions
        olfactory nerve transmits qu-octrit → qu-septit coupling (56 dimensions)
        NO thalamic gating: signal arrives directly
        piriform cortex performs pattern matching → smell identification
        amygdala fires emotional response (12ms: fastest in organism)
        entorhinal cortex encodes to hippocampus (15ms: memory formation)
        OFC performs conscious identification (100ms: naming)
        hypothalamus evaluates metabolic significance
        behavior emerges: approach, avoid, eat, flee, or remember

    the 10 Hz rate matches breathing:
        each inhale brings new odorant molecules to the epithelium
        each exhale clears the old sample
        the olfactory heartbeat IS the breathing cycle
        if breathing stops, olfaction stops
        apnea = olfactory blindness
